# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jpeg-compression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A **discrete cosine transform** (**DCT**) expresses a finite sequence of data points in terms of a sum of cosine functions oscillating at different frequencies.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT, first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, is a widely used transformation technique in signal processing and data compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are also important to numerous other applications in science and engineering, such as digital signal processing, telecommunication devices, reducing network bandwidth usage, and spectral methods for the numerical solution of partial differential equations.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A DCT is a Fourier-related transform similar to the discrete Fourier transform (DFT), but using only real numbers.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCTs are generally related to Fourier series coefficients of a periodically and symmetrically extended sequence whereas DFTs are related to Fourier series coefficients of only periodically extended sequences.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are equivalent to DFTs of roughly twice the length, operating on real data with even symmetry (since the Fourier transform of a real and even function is real and even), whereas in some variants the input or output data are shifted by half a sample.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] There are eight standard DCT variants, of which four are common.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The most common variant of discrete cosine transform is the type-II DCT, which is often called simply *the DCT*.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This was the original DCT as first proposed by Ahmed.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Its inverse, the type-III DCT, is correspondingly often called simply *the inverse DCT* or *the IDCT*.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Two related transforms are the discrete sine transform (DST), which is equivalent to a DFT of real and odd functions, and the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), which is based on a DCT of overlapping data.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Multidimensional DCTs (MD DCTs) are developed to extend the concept of DCT to multidimensional signals.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A variety of fast algorithms have been developed to reduce the computational complexity of implementing DCT.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] One of these is the integer DCT (IntDCT), an integer approximation of the standard DCT, used in several ISO/IEC and ITU-T international standards.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT compression, also known as block compression, compresses data in sets of discrete DCT blocks.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT blocks sizes including 8 × 8 pixels for the standard DCT, and varied integer DCT sizes between 4 × 4 and 32 × 32 pixels.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT has a strong *energy compaction* property, capable of achieving high quality at high data compression ratios.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] However, blocky compression artifacts can appear when heavy DCT compression is applied.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT was first conceived by Nasir Ahmed while working at Kansas State University.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The concept was proposed to the National Science Foundation in 1972.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT was originally intended for image compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Ahmed developed a practical DCT algorithm with his PhD students T.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Rao at the University of Texas at Arlington in 1973.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] They presented their results in a January 1974 paper, titled *Discrete Cosine Transform*.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] It described what is now called the type-II DCT (DCT-II), as well as the type-III inverse DCT (IDCT).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Since its introduction in 1974, there has been significant research on the DCT.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In 1977, Wen-Hsiung Chen published a paper with C.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Fralick presenting a fast DCT algorithm.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Further developments include a 1978 paper by M.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] These research papers, along with the original 1974 Ahmed paper and the 1977 Chen paper, were cited by the Joint Photographic Experts Group as the basis for JPEG's lossy image compression algorithm in 1992.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The discrete sine transform (DST) was derived from the DCT, by replacing the Neumann condition at *x=0* with a Dirichlet condition.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DST was described in the 1974 DCT paper by Ahmed, Natarajan and Rao.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A type-I DST (DST-I) was later described by Anil K.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Jain in 1976, and a type-II DST (DST-II) was then described by H.B.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Robinson adapted the DCT for inter-frame motion-compensated video coding.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Jain further developed motion-compensated DCT video compression, also called block motion compensation.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This led to Chen developing a practical video compression algorithm, called motion-compensated DCT or adaptive scene coding, in 1981.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Motion-compensated DCT later became the standard coding technique for video compression from the late 1980s onwards.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A DCT variant, the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), was developed by John P.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Bradley at the University of Surrey in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The MDCT is used in most modern audio compression formats, such as Dolby Digital (AC-3), MP3 (which uses a hybrid DCT-FFT algorithm), Advanced Audio Coding (AAC), and Vorbis (Ogg).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Nasir Ahmed also developed a lossless DCT algorithm with Giridhar Mandyam and Neeraj Magotra at the University of New Mexico in 1995.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This allows the DCT technique to be used for lossless compression of images.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] It is a modification of the original DCT algorithm, and incorporates elements of inverse DCT and delta modulation.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] It is a more effective lossless compression algorithm than entropy coding.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT is the most widely used transformation technique in signal processing, and by far the most widely used linear transform in data compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT compression standards are used in digital media technologies, such as digital images, digital photos, digital video, streaming media, digital television, streaming television, video on demand (VOD), digital cinema, high-definition video (HD video), and high-definition television (HDTV).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT, and in particular the DCT-II, is often used in signal and image processing, especially for lossy compression, because it has a strong *energy compaction* property.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In typical applications, most of the signal information tends to be concentrated in a few low-frequency components of the DCT.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] For strongly correlated Markov processes, the DCT can approach the compaction efficiency of the Karhunen-Loève transform (which is optimal in the decorrelation sense).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] As explained below, this stems from the boundary conditions implicit in the cosine functions.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are widely employed in solving partial differential equations by spectral methods, where the different variants of the DCT correspond to slightly different even and odd boundary conditions at the two ends of the array.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are closely related to Chebyshev polynomials, and fast DCT algorithms (below) are used in Chebyshev approximation of arbitrary functions by series of Chebyshev polynomials, for example in Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT is widely used in many applications, which include the following.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-II is an important image compression technique.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] It is used in image compression standards such as JPEG, and video compression standards such as H.26x, MJPEG, MPEG, DV, Theora and Daala.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] There, the two-dimensional DCT-II of $N\times N$ blocks are computed and the results are quantized and entropy coded.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In this case, N is typically 8 and the DCT-II formula is applied to each row and column of the block.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The result is an 8 × 8 transform coefficient array in which the $(0,0)$ element (top-left) is the DC (zero-frequency) component and entries with increasing vertical and horizontal index values represent higher vertical and horizontal spatial frequencies.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The integer DCT, an integer approximation of the DCT, is used in Advanced Video Coding (AVC), introduced in 2003, and High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC), introduced in 2013.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The integer DCT is also used in the High Efficiency Image Format (HEIF), which uses a subset of the HEVC video coding format for coding still images.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] HEVC and HEIF use varied block sizes between 4 x 4 and 32 x 32 pixels.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] As of 2019, AVC is by far the most commonly used format for the recording, compression and distribution of video content, used by 91% of video developers, followed by HEVC which is used by 43% of developers.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Multidimensional DCTs (MD DCTs) have several applications, mainly 3-D DCTs such as the 3-D DCT-II, which has several new applications like Hyperspectral Imaging coding systems, variable temporal length 3-D DCT coding, video coding algorithms, adaptive video coding and 3-D Compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Due to enhancement in the hardware, software and introduction of several fast algorithms, the necessity of using MD DCTs is rapidly increasing.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT-IV has gained popularity for its applications in fast implementation of real-valued polyphase filtering banks, lapped orthogonal transform and cosine-modulated wavelet bases.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT plays an important role in digital signal processing specifically data compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT is widely implemented in digital signal processors (DSP), as well as digital signal processing software.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Many companies have developed DSPs based on DCT technology.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are widely used for applications such as encoding, decoding, video, audio, multiplexing, control signals, signaling, and analog-to-digital conversion.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs are also commonly used for high-definition television (HDTV) encoder/decoder chips.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A common issue with DCT compression in digital media are blocky compression artifacts, caused by DCT blocks.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In a DCT algorithm, an image (or frame in an image sequence) is divided into square blocks which are processed independently from each other, then the DCT blocks is taken within each block and the resulting DCT coefficients are quantized.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This process can cause blocking artifacts, primarily at high data compression ratios.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This can also cause the mosquito noise effect, commonly found in digital video.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT blocks are often used in glitch art.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The artist Rosa Menkman makes use of DCT-based compression artifacts in her glitch art, particularly the DCT blocks found in most digital media formats such as JPEG digital images and MP3 audio.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Another example is *Jpegs* by German photographer Thomas Ruff, which uses intentional JPEG artifacts as the basis of the picture's style.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Like any Fourier-related transform, DCTs express a function or a signal in terms of a sum of sinusoids with different frequencies and amplitudes.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Like the DFT, a DCT operates on a function at a finite number of discrete data points.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The obvious distinction between a DCT and a DFT is that the former uses only cosine functions, while the latter uses both cosines and sines (in the form of complex exponentials).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] However, this visible difference is merely a consequence of a deeper distinction: a DCT implies different boundary conditions from the DFT or other related transforms.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The Fourier-related transforms that operate on a function over a finite domain, such as the DFT or DCT or a Fourier series, can be thought of as implicitly defining an *extension* of that function outside the domain.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] That is, once you write a function $f(x)$ as a sum of sinusoids, you can evaluate that sum at any x , even for x where the original $f(x)$ was not specified.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DFT, like the Fourier series, implies a periodic extension of the original function.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A DCT, like a cosine transform, implies an even extension of the original function.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] However, because DCTs operate on *finite*, *discrete* sequences, two issues arise that do not apply for the continuous cosine transform.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] First, one has to specify whether the function is even or odd at *both* the left and right boundaries of the domain (i.e. the min-*n* and max-*n* boundaries in the definitions below, respectively).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Second, one has to specify around *what point* the function is even or odd.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In particular, consider a sequence *abcd* of four equally spaced data points, and say that we specify an even *left* boundary.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] There are two sensible possibilities: either the data are even about the sample *a*, in which case the even extension is *dcbabcd*, or the data are even about the point *halfway* between *a* and the previous point, in which case the even extension is *dcbaabcd* (*a* is repeated).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Each boundary can be either even or odd (2 choices per boundary) and can be symmetric about a data point or the point halfway between two data points (2 choices per boundary), for a total of 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 = 16 possibilities.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] These choices lead to all the standard variations of DCTs and also discrete sine transforms (DSTs).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Half of these possibilities, those where the *left* boundary is even, correspond to the 8 types of DCT; the other half are the 8 types of DST.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] These different boundary conditions strongly affect the applications of the transform and lead to uniquely useful properties for the various DCT types.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Most directly, when using Fourier-related transforms to solve partial differential equations by spectral methods, the boundary conditions are directly specified as a part of the problem being solved.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Or, for the MDCT (based on the type-IV DCT), the boundary conditions are intimately involved in the MDCT's critical property of time-domain aliasing cancellation.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In a more subtle fashion, the boundary conditions are responsible for the *energy compactification* properties that make DCTs useful for image and audio compression, because the boundaries affect the rate of convergence of any Fourier-like series.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In particular, it is well known that any discontinuities in a function reduce the rate of convergence of the Fourier series so that more sinusoids are needed to represent the function with a given accuracy.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The same principle governs the usefulness of the DFT and other transforms for signal compression; the smoother a function is, the fewer terms in its DFT or DCT are required to represent it accurately, and the more it can be compressed.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] However, the implicit periodicity of the DFT means that discontinuities usually occur at the boundaries: any random segment of a signal is unlikely to have the same value at both the left and right boundaries.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In contrast, a DCT where *both* boundaries are even *always* yields a continuous extension at the boundaries (although the slope is generally discontinuous).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This is why DCTs, and in particular DCTs of types I, II, V, and VI (the types that have two even boundaries) generally perform better for signal compression than DFTs and DSTs.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In practice, a type-II DCT is usually preferred for such applications, in part for reasons of computational convenience.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Formally, the discrete cosine transform is a linear, invertible function $f:\mathbb {R} ^{N}\to \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ (where $\mathbb {R}$ denotes the set of real numbers), or equivalently an invertible N × N square matrix.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] There are several variants of the DCT with slightly modified definitions.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-I is exactly equivalent (up to an overall scale factor of 2), to a DFT of $2(N-1)$ real numbers with even symmetry.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, a DCT-I of $N=5$ real numbers $a\ b\ c\ d\ e$ is exactly equivalent to a DFT of eight real numbers $a\ b\ c\ d\ e\ d\ c\ b$ (even symmetry), divided by two.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Note, however, that the DCT-I is not defined for N less than 2, while all other DCT types are defined for any positive N .
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Thus, the DCT-I corresponds to the boundary conditions: $x_{n}$ is even around $n=0$ and even around $n=N-1$ ; similarly for $X_{k}$ .
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-II is probably the most commonly used form, and is often simply referred to as the *DCT*.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This transform is exactly equivalent (up to an overall scale factor of 2) to a DFT of $4N$ real inputs of even symmetry, where the even-indexed elements are zero.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCT-II transformation is also possible using $2N$ signal followed by a multiplication by half shift.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Some authors further multiply the $X_{0}$ term by $1/{\sqrt {N\,}}\,$ and multiply the rest of the matrix by an overall scale factor of ${\textstyle {\sqrt {{2}/{N}}}}$ (see below for the corresponding change in DCT-III).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This makes the DCT-II matrix orthogonal, but breaks the direct correspondence with a real-even DFT of half-shifted input.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This is the normalization used by Matlab.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In many applications, such as JPEG, the scaling is arbitrary because scale factors can be combined with a subsequent computational step (e.g. the quantization step in JPEG), and a scaling can be chosen that allows the DCT to be computed with fewer multiplications.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-II implies the boundary conditions: $x_{n}$ is even around $n=-1/2$ and even around $n=N-1/2\,$ ; $X_{k}$ is even around $k=0$ and odd around $k=N$ .
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Because it is the inverse of DCT-II up to a scale factor (see below), this form is sometimes simply referred to as the inverse DCT (IDCT).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This makes the DCT-III matrix orthogonal, but breaks the direct correspondence with a real-even DFT of half-shifted output.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A variant of the DCT-IV, where data from different transforms are *overlapped*, is called the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-IV implies the boundary conditions: $x_{n}$ is even around $n=-1/2$ and odd around $n=N-1/2$ ; similarly for $X_{k}$ .
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] DCTs of types I–IV treat both boundaries consistently regarding the point of symmetry: they are even or odd around either a data point for both boundaries or halfway between two data points for both boundaries.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] By contrast, DCTs of types V-VIII imply boundaries that are even or odd around a data point for one boundary and halfway between two data points for the other boundary.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In other words, DCT types I–IV are equivalent to real-even DFTs of even order (regardless of whether N is even or odd), since the corresponding DFT is of length $2(N-1)$ (for DCT-I) or $4N$ (for DCT-II and III) or $8N$ (for DCT-IV).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The four additional types of discrete cosine transform correspond essentially to real-even DFTs of logically odd order, which have factors of $N\pm {1}/{2}$ in the denominators of the cosine arguments.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] However, these variants seem to be rarely used in practice.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] One reason, perhaps, is that FFT algorithms for odd-length DFTs are generally more complicated than FFT algorithms for even-length DFTs (e.g., the simplest radix-2 algorithms are only for even lengths), and this increased intricacy carries over to the DCTs as described below.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Not that the trivial real-even array, a length-one DFT (odd length) of a single number a , corresponds to a DCT-V of length $N=1$ .
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Using the normalization conventions above, the inverse of DCT-I is DCT-I multiplied by 2/(*N* − 1).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse of DCT-IV is DCT-IV multiplied by 2/*N*.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse of DCT-II is DCT-III multiplied by 2/*N* and vice versa.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Like for the DFT, the normalization factor in front of these transform definitions is merely a convention and differs between treatments.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, some authors multiply the transforms by ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2/N}}}$ so that the inverse does not require any additional multiplicative factor.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Combined with appropriate factors of √2 (see above), this can be used to make the transform matrix orthogonal.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Multidimensional variants of the various DCT types follow straightforwardly from the one-dimensional definitions: they are simply a separable product (equivalently, a composition) of DCTs along each dimension.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, a two-dimensional DCT-II of an image or a matrix is simply the one-dimensional DCT-II, from above, performed along the rows and then along the columns (or vice versa).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse of a multi-dimensional DCT is just a separable product of the inverses of the corresponding one-dimensional DCTs (see above), e.g., the one-dimensional inverses applied along one dimension at a time in a row-column algorithm.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Technically, computing a two-, three- (or -multi) dimensional DCT by sequences of one-dimensional DCTs along each dimension is known as a *row-column* algorithm.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] As with multidimensional FFT algorithms, however, there exist other methods to compute the same thing while performing the computations in a different order (i.e., interleaving or combining the algorithms for the different dimensions).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Owing to the rapid growth in the applications based on the 3-D DCT, several fast algorithms have been developed for the computation of 3-D DCT-II.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Vector-Radix algorithms are applied for computing M-D DCT to reduce the computational complexity and to increase the computational speed.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Vector-Radix Decimation in Frequency (VR DIF) is an example of an algorithm to compute a 3-D DCT-II efficiently.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In order to apply the VR DIF algorithm, the input data must be formulated and rearranged as follows.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The transform size *N × N × N* is assumed to be 2.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The adjacent figure shows the four stages that are involved in calculating 3-D DCT-II using VR DIF algorithm.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The first stage is the 3-D reordering using the index mapping illustrated by the above equations.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The second stage is the butterfly calculation.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Each butterfly calculates eight points together as shown in the figure just below, where $c(\varphi _{i})=\cos(\varphi _{i})$ .
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The whole 3-D DCT calculation needs $~[\log _{2}N]~$ stages, and each stage involves $~{\tfrac {1}{8}}\ N^{3}~$ butterflies.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Each butterfly requires seven real multiplications (including trivial multiplications) and 24 real additions (including trivial additions).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The conventional method to calculate MD-DCT-II is using a Row-Column-Frame (RCF) approach, which is computationally complex and less productive on most recent advanced hardware platforms.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The VR DIF algorithm requires fewer multiplications than the RCF algorithm.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The total number of multiplications associated with the 3-D DCT VR algorithm is less than that associated with the RCF approach by more than 40%.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In addition, the RCF approach involves matrix transpose and more indexing and data swapping than the VR DIF algorithm.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This makes the 3-D DCT VR algorithm more efficient and better suited for 3-D applications that involve the 3-D DCT-II, such as video compression and other 3-D image processing applications.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The main consideration in choosing a fast algorithm is to avoid computational and structural complexities.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] As the technology of computers and DSPs advances, the execution time of arithmetic operations (multiplications and additions) improves and regular computational structure becomes the most important factor.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Therefore, although the above proposed 3-D VR algorithm does not achieve the theoretical lower bound on the number of multiplications, it has a simpler computational structure as compared to other 3-D DCT algorithms.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] It can be implemented in place using a single butterfly and possesses the properties of the Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithm in 3-D.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Hence, the 3-D VR presents a good choice for reducing arithmetic operations in the calculation of the 3-D DCT-II, while keeping the simple structure that characterizes butterfly-style Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithms.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The image to the right shows a combination of horizontal and vertical frequencies for an 8 × 8 $(~N_{1}=N_{2}=8~)$ two-dimensional DCT.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Each step from left to right and top to bottom is an increase in frequency by a half-cycle.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, moving right one from the top-left square yields a half-cycle increase in the horizontal frequency.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Another move to the right yields two half-cycles.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A move down yields two half-cycles horizontally and a half-cycle vertically.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The source data (8 × 8) is transformed to a linear combination of these 64 frequency squares.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The MD DCT-IV is an extension of 1-D DCT-IV onto an M-dimensional domain.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] We can compute the MD DCT-IV using the regular row-column method, or we can use the polynomial transform method for fast and efficient computation.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The main idea of this algorithm is to use the polynomial transform to directly convert the multidimensional DCT into a series of 1-D DCTs.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Although the direct application of these formulas would require $~{\mathcal {O}}(N^{2})~$ operations, it is possible to compute the same thing with only $~{\mathcal {O}}(N\log N)~$ complexity by factorizing the computation similarly to the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] One can also compute DCTs via FFTs combined with $~{\mathcal {O}}(N)~$ pre- and post-processing steps.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In general, $~{\mathcal {O}}(N\log N)~$ methods to compute DCTs are known as fast cosine transform (FCT) algorithms.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] The most efficient algorithms, in principle, are usually those that are specialized directly for the DCT, as opposed to using an ordinary FFT plus $~{\mathcal {O}}(N)~$ extra operations (see below for an exception).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] This can even be done automatically (Frigo & Johnson 2005).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Algorithms based on the Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithm are most common, but any other FFT algorithm is also applicable.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, the Winograd FFT algorithm leads to minimal-multiplication algorithms for the DFT, albeit generally at the cost of more additions, and a similar algorithm was proposed by (Feig & Winograd 1992a) for the DCT.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Because the algorithms for DFTs, DCTs, and similar transforms are all so closely related, any improvement in algorithms for one transform will theoretically lead to immediate gains for the other transforms as well (Duhamel & Vetterli 1990).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] While DCT algorithms that employ an unmodified FFT often have some theoretical overhead compared to the best specialized DCT algorithms, the former also have a distinct advantage: Highly optimized FFT programs are widely available.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Thus, in practice, it is often easier to obtain high performance for general lengths N with FFT-based algorithms.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Specialized DCT algorithms, on the other hand, see widespread use for transforms of small, fixed sizes such as the 8 × 8 DCT-II used in JPEG compression, or the small DCTs (or MDCTs) typically used in audio compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] In fact, even the DCT algorithms using an ordinary FFT are sometimes equivalent to pruning the redundant operations from a larger FFT of real-symmetric data, and they can even be optimal from the perspective of arithmetic counts.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] For example, a type-II DCT is equivalent to a DFT of size $~4N~$ with real-even symmetry whose even-indexed elements are zero.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Because the even-indexed elements are zero, this radix-4 step is exactly the same as a split-radix step.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] If the subsequent size $~N~$ real-data FFT is also performed by a real-data split-radix algorithm (as in Sorensen et al.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] (1987)), then the resulting algorithm actually matches what was long the lowest published arithmetic count for the power-of-two DCT-II ( $~2N\log _{2}N-N+2~$ real-arithmetic operations).
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] A recent reduction in the operation count to $~{\tfrac {17}{9}}N\log _{2}N+{\mathcal {O}}(N)$ also uses a real-data FFT.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] So, there is nothing intrinsically bad about computing the DCT via an FFT from an arithmetic perspective – it is sometimes merely a question of whether the corresponding FFT algorithm is optimal.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Consider this 8 × 8 grayscale image of capital letter A.
[src:jpeg-compression/discrete-cosine-transform] Each basis function is multiplied by its coefficient and then this product is added to the final image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The JPEG 2000 project was motivated by Ricoh's submission in 1995 of the CREW (compression with reversible embedded wavelets) algorithm to the standardization effort of JPEG LS.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Ultimately the LOCO-I algorithm was selected as the basis for JPEG LS, but many of the features of CREW ended up in the JPEG 2000 standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 codestreams are regions of interest that offer several mechanisms to support spatial random access or region of interest access at varying degrees of granularity.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] It is possible to store different parts of the same picture using different quality.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 is a compression standard based on a discrete wavelet transform (DWT).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The standard could be adapted for motion imaging video compression with the Motion JPEG 2000 extension.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 technology was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] However, JPEG 2000 is generally not supported in web browsers for web pages as of 2024, and hence is not generally used on the World Wide Web.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Nevertheless, for those with PDF support, web browsers generally support JPEG 2000 in PDFs.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Unlike the legacy **.jpg** format, which offers basic image compression without support for embedded metadata or access control, JPEG 2000 introduces advanced container options such as **.jp2** and .jpf.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Of these, the **.jpf** extension offers a significantly more powerful and extensible framework.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] It supports high-fidelity wavelet compression, layered and tiled image structures, region-of-interest encoding, and remote streaming via the JPEG 2000 Interactive Protocol (JPIP).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The **.jpf** extension can be used to embed machine-readable consent flags, secure face hashes, and cryptographic signatures.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] This format can be used along with JPIP for time-limited, revocable access to visual data.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] While there is a modest increase in compression performance of JPEG 2000 compared to JPEG, the main advantage offered by JPEG 2000 is the significant flexibility of the codestream.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] By ordering the codestream in various ways, applications can achieve significant performance increases.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] However, as a consequence of this flexibility, JPEG 2000 requires codecs that are complex and computationally demanding.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Another difference, in comparison with JPEG, is in terms of visual artifacts: JPEG 2000 only produces ringing artifacts, manifested as blur and rings near edges in the image, while JPEG produces both ringing artifacts and 'blocking' artifacts, due to its 8×8 blocks.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 has been published as an ISO standard, ISO/IEC 15444.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The cost of obtaining all documents for the standard has been estimated at 2,718 CHF (US$2,720 as of 2015).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 decomposes the image into a multiple resolution representation in the course of its compression process.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] This pyramid representation can be put to use for other image presentation purposes beyond compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] These features are more commonly known as *progressive decoding* and *signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) scalability*.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 provides efficient codestream organizations which are progressive by pixel accuracy and by image resolution (or by image size).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] This allows the viewer to see a lower quality version of the final picture before the whole file has been downloaded.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The quality improves progressively as more data is downloaded from the source.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Like the Lossless JPEG standard, the JPEG 2000 standard provides both lossless and lossy compression in a single compression architecture.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Lossless compression is provided by the use of a reversible integer wavelet transform in JPEG 2000.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The JP2 and JPX file formats allow for handling of color-space information, metadata, and for interactivity in networked applications as developed in the JPEG Part 9 JPIP protocol.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 supports bit depths of 1 to 38 bits per component.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Supported color spaces include monochrome, 3 types of YCbCr, sRGB, PhotoYCC, CMY(K), YCCK and CIELab.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] It also later added support for CIEJab (CIECAM02), e-sRGB, ROMM, YPbPr and others.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Full support for transparency and alpha planes.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The aim of JPEG 2000 is not only improving compression performance over JPEG but also adding (or improving) features such as scalability and editability.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000's improvement in compression performance relative to the original JPEG standard is actually rather modest and should not ordinarily be the primary consideration for evaluating the design.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Very low and very high compression rates are supported in JPEG 2000.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The ability of the design to handle a very large range of effective bit rates is one of the strengths of JPEG 2000.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] For example, to reduce the number of bits for a picture below a certain amount, the advisable thing to do with the first JPEG standard is to reduce the resolution of the input image before encoding it.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] That is unnecessary when using JPEG 2000, because JPEG 2000 already does this automatically through its multi-resolution decomposition structure.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The following sections describe the algorithm of JPEG 2000.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] According to the Royal Library of the Netherlands, "the current JP2 format specification leaves room for multiple interpretations when it comes to the support of ICC profiles, and the handling of grid resolution information".
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Initially images have to be transformed from the RGB color space to another color space, leading to three *components* that are handled separately.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Reversible Color Transform (RCT) uses a modified YUV color space (almost the same as YCGCO) that does not introduce quantization errors, so it is fully reversible.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Proper implementation of the RCT requires that numbers be rounded as specified and cannot be expressed exactly in matrix form.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The RCT shall be used only with the 5/3 wavelet transform.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] If R, G, and B are normalized to the same precision, then numeric precision of CB and CR is one bit greater than the precision of the original components.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] This increase in precision is necessary to ensure reversibility.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The chrominance components can be, but do not necessarily have to be, downscaled in resolution; in fact, since the wavelet transformation already separates images into scales, downsampling is more effectively handled by dropping the finest wavelet scale.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] This step is called *multiple component transformation* in the JPEG 2000 language since its usage is not restricted to the RGB color model.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] After color transformation, the image is split into so-called *tiles*, rectangular regions of the image that are transformed and encoded separately.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Tiles can be any size, and it is also possible to consider the whole image as one single tile.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Once the size is chosen, all the tiles will have the same size (except optionally those on the right and bottom borders).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Dividing the image into tiles is advantageous in that the decoder will need less memory to decode the image and it can opt to decode only selected tiles to achieve a partial decoding of the image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The disadvantage of this approach is that the quality of the picture decreases due to a lower peak signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Using many tiles can create a blocking effect similar to the older JPEG 1992 standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] These tiles are then wavelet-transformed to an arbitrary depth, in contrast to JPEG 1992 which uses an 8×8 block-size discrete cosine transform.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] *reversible*: a rounded version of the biorthogonal Le Gall–Tabatabai (LGT) 5/3 wavelet transform (developed by Didier Le Gall and Ali J.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] It uses only integer coefficients, so the output does not require rounding (quantization) and so it does not introduce any quantization noise.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The wavelet transforms are implemented by the lifting scheme or by convolution.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] After the wavelet transform, the coefficients are scalar-quantized to reduce the number of bits to represent them, at the expense of quality.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The output is a set of integer numbers which have to be encoded bit-by-bit.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The parameter that can be changed to set the final quality is the quantization step: the greater the step, the greater is the compression and the loss of quality.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] With a quantization step that equals 1, no quantization is performed (it is used in lossless compression).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The result of the previous process is a collection of *sub-bands* which represent several approximation scales.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] A sub-band is a set of *coefficients*—real numbers which represent aspects of the image associated with a certain frequency range as well as a spatial area of the image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The quantized sub-bands are split further into *precincts*, rectangular regions in the wavelet domain.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] They are typically sized so that they provide an efficient way to access only part of the (reconstructed) image, though this is not a requirement.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Precincts are split further into *code blocks*.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Code blocks are in a single sub-band and have equal sizes—except those located at the edges of the image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The encoder has to encode the bits of all quantized coefficients of a code block, starting with the most significant bits and progressing to less significant bits by a process called the *EBCOT* scheme.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] *EBCOT* here stands for *Embedded Block Coding with Optimal Truncation*.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The three passes are called *Significance Propagation*, *Magnitude Refinement* and *Cleanup* pass, respectively.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] In lossless mode all bit planes have to be encoded by the EBCOT, and no bit planes can be dropped.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The bits selected by these coding passes then get encoded by a context-driven binary arithmetic coder, namely the binary MQ-coder (as also employed by JBIG2).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The context of a coefficient is formed by the state of its eight neighbors in the code block.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The result is a bit-stream that is split into *packets* where a *packet* groups selected passes of all code blocks from a precinct into one indivisible unit.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Packets are the key to quality scalability (i.e., packets containing less significant bits can be discarded to achieve lower bit rates and higher distortion).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Packets from all sub-bands are then collected in so-called *layers*.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Thus, layers define the progression by image quality within the codestream.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The problem is now to find the optimal packet length for all code blocks which minimizes the overall distortion in a way that the generated target bitrate equals the demanded bit rate.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Furthermore, the length of the resulting codestream gets measured.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] This forms for each code block a graph in the rate–distortion plane, giving image quality over bitstream length.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The optimal selection for the truncation points, thus for the packet-build-up points is then given by defining critical *slopes* of these curves, and picking all those coding passes whose curve in the rate–distortion graph is steeper than the given critical slope.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] This method can be seen as a special application of the method of *Lagrange multiplier* which is used for optimization problems under constraints.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The Lagrange multiplier, typically denoted by λ, turns out to be the critical slope, the constraint is the demanded target bitrate, and the value to optimize is the overall distortion.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Packets can be reordered almost arbitrarily in the JPEG 2000 bit-stream; this gives the encoder as well as image servers a high degree of freedom.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Already encoded images can be sent over networks with arbitrary bit rates by using a layer-progressive encoding order.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] On the other hand, color components can be moved back in the bit-stream; lower resolutions (corresponding to low-frequency sub-bands) could be sent first for image previewing.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Finally, spatial browsing of large images is possible through appropriate tile or partition selection.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] All these operations do not require any re-encoding but only byte-wise copy operations.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Compared to the previous JPEG standard, JPEG 2000 delivers a typical compression gain in the range of 20%, depending on the image characteristics.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Higher-resolution images tend to benefit more, where JPEG 2000's spatial-redundancy prediction can contribute more to the compression process.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] In very low-bitrate applications, studies have shown JPEG 2000 to be outperformed by the intra-frame coding mode of H.264.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 is much more complicated in terms of computational complexity in comparison with JPEG standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Tiling, color component transform, discrete wavelet transform, and quantization could be done pretty fast, though entropy codec is time-consuming and quite complicated.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] EBCOT context modelling and arithmetic MQ-coder take most of the time of JPEG 2000 codec.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Fast JPEG 2000 encoding on the CPU makes use of hardware-acceleration with AVX/SSE and uses multithreading to process each tile in a separate thread.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The fastest solutions utilize both the CPU and GPU to achieve high performance benchmarks.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Similar to JPEG-1, JPEG 2000 defines both a file format and a codestream.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Whereas JPEG 2000 entirely describes the image samples, JPEG-1 includes additional meta-information such as the resolution of the image or the color space that has been used to encode the image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 images should—if stored as files—be boxed in the JPEG 2000 file format, where they get the **.jp2** extension.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The part-2 extension to JPEG 2000 (ISO/IEC 15444-2) enriches the file format by including mechanisms for animation or composition of several codestreams into one single image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] This extended file format is called JPX, and should use the file extension **.jpf**, although **.jpx** is also used.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] There is no standardized extension for codestream data because codestream data is not to be considered to be stored in files in the first place, though when done for testing purposes, the extension **.jpc**, **.j2k** or **.j2c** is commonly used.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The .jpf file extension is an alternative container format for JPEG 2000 images, supporting the extended feature set defined in Part 2 of the ISO/IEC 15444 standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] While functionally similar to `.jp2`, the `.jpf` format is commonly used in applications requiring wavelet compression, layered image structures, embedded metadata, and support for the JPEG 2000 Interactive Protocol (JPIP).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] It is often found in domains such as geospatial imaging, digital cinema, and forensic science.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The `.jpf` format supports revocable image access through a combination of metadata and network streaming mechanisms.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] These features enable greater control over how images are accessed and used, particularly in the context of artificial intelligence and identity protection.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] These mechanisms allow `.jpf` images to function as consent-aware media containers, offering post-publication control over AI training usage, facial recognition indexing, and unauthorized redistribution.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Despite these technical capabilities, adoption of `.jpf` in consumer imaging software remains limited due to minimal support in mainstream browsers, mobile operating systems, and cloud platforms.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] For traditional JPEG, additional metadata, e.g. lighting and exposure conditions, is kept in an application marker in the Exif format specified by the JEITA.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 chooses a different route, encoding the same metadata in XML form.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The reference between the Exif tags and the XML elements is standardized by the ISO TC42 committee in the standard 12234-1.4.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Extensible Metadata Platform can also be embedded in JPEG 2000.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] ISO 15444 is covered by patents and the specification lists 17 patent holders, but the contributing companies and organizations agreed that licenses for its first part—the core coding system—can be obtained free of charge from all contributors.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] However, this is not a formal guarantee.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] In addition, license and royalties may be required to use some extensions.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Extensions for secure image transfer, *JPSEC* (ISO/IEC 15444-8), enhanced error-correction schemes for wireless applications, *JPWL* (ISO/IEC 15444-11) and extensions for encoding of volumetric images, *JP3D* (ISO/IEC 15444-10) are also already available from the ISO.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] In 2005, a JPEG 2000–based image browsing protocol, called JPIP was published as ISO/IEC 15444-9.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Within this framework, only selected regions of potentially huge images have to be transmitted from an image server on the request of a client, thus reducing the required bandwidth.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JPEG 2000 data may also be streamed using the ECWP and ECWPS protocols found within the ERDAS ECW/JP2 SDK.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Motion JPEG 2000, (MJ2), originally defined in Part 3 of the ISO Standard for JPEG2000 (ISO/IEC 15444-3:2002,) as a standalone document, has now been expressed by ISO/IEC 15444-3:2002/Amd 2:2003 in terms of the ISO Base format, ISO/IEC 15444-12 and in ITU-T Recommendation T.802.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] It specifies the use of the JPEG 2000 format for timed sequences of images (motion sequences), possibly combined with audio, and composed into an overall presentation.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] It also defines a file format, based on ISO base media file format (ISO 15444-12).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Filename extensions for Motion JPEG 2000 video files are **.mj2** and **.mjp2** according to RFC 3745.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] It is an open ISO standard and an advanced update to MJPEG (or MJ), which was based on the legacy JPEG format.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Unlike common video formats, such as MPEG-4 Part 2, WMV, and H.264, MJ2 does not employ temporal or inter-frame compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Instead, each frame is an independent entity encoded by either a lossy or lossless variant of JPEG 2000.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Its physical structure does not depend on time ordering, but it does employ a separate profile to complement the data.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] For audio, it supports LPCM encoding, as well as various MPEG-4 variants, as "raw" or complement data.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Motion JPEG 2000 (often referenced as MJ2 or MJP2) is considered as a digital archival format by the Library of Congress though MXF_OP1a_JP2_LL (lossless JPEG 2000 wrapped in MXF operational pattern 1a) is preferred by the LOC Packard Campus for Audio-Visual Conservation.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] ISO/IEC 15444-12 is identical with ISO/IEC 14496-12 (MPEG-4 Part 12) and it defines ISO base media file format.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] For example, Motion JPEG 2000 file format, MP4 file format or 3GP file format are also based on this ISO base media file format.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] The Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC) has defined a metadata standard for georeferencing JPEG 2000 images with embedded XML using the Geography Markup Language (GML) format: *GML in JPEG 2000 for Geographic Imagery Encoding (GMLJP2)*, version 1.0.0, dated 2006-01-18.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Version 2.0, entitled *GML in JPEG 2000 (GMLJP2) Encoding Standard Part 1: Core* was approved 2014-06-30.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] JP2 and JPX files containing GMLJP2 markup can be located and displayed in the correct position on the Earth's surface by a suitable Geographic Information System (GIS), in a similar way to GeoTIFF and GTG images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] IrfanView is provided as freeware, but only for *private, non-commercial use* (that means at home), educational use (schools, universities, museums, libraries) and for use in charity or humanitarian organisations including fire departments and national park services.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Adobe Photoshop CS2 and CS3's official JPEG 2000 plug-in package is not installed by default and must be manually copied from the install disk/folder to the Plug-Ins > File Formats folder.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-2000] Safari 18 dropped support for JPEG-2000 images.[4] Older versions of Safari since Safari 5 supported JPEG-2000 images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The Joint Photographic Experts Group created the standard in 1992, based on the discrete cosine transform (DCT) algorithm.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] JPEG was largely responsible for the proliferation of digital images and digital photos across the Internet and later social media.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] JPEG compression is used in a number of image file formats.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] JPEG/Exif is the most common image format used by digital cameras and other photographic image capture devices; along with JPEG/JFIF, it is the most common format for storing and transmitting photographic images on the World Wide Web.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] These format variations are often not distinguished and are simply called JPEG.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The MIME media type for JPEG is "image/jpeg", except in older Internet Explorer versions, which provide a MIME type of "image/pjpeg" when uploading JPEG images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] JPEG files usually have a filename extension of "jpg" or "jpeg".
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] JPEG/JFIF supports a maximum image size of 65,535×65,535 pixels, hence up to 4 gigapixels for an aspect ratio of 1:1.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In 2000, the JPEG group introduced a format intended to be a successor, JPEG 2000, but it was unable to replace the original JPEG as the dominant image standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The original JPEG specification published in 1992 implements processes from various earlier research papers and patents cited by the CCITT (now ITU-T) and Joint Photographic Experts Group.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The basis for JPEG's lossy compression algorithm is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which was first proposed by Nasir Ahmed as an image compression technique in 1972.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Ahmed published the DCT algorithm with T.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Rao in a 1974 paper, which is cited in the JPEG specification.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The JPEG specification cites patents from several companies.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The following patents provided the basis for its arithmetic coding algorithm.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The JPEG specification also cites three other patents from IBM.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Other companies cited as patent holders include AT&T (two patents) and Canon Inc.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Absent from the list is U.S. patent 4,698,672, filed by Compression Labs' Wen-Hsiung Chen and Daniel J.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The patent describes a DCT-based image compression algorithm, and would later be a cause of controversy in 2002 (see *Patent controversy* below).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] However, the JPEG specification did cite two earlier research papers by Wen-Hsiung Chen, published in 1977 and 1984.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] "JPEG" stands for Joint Photographic Experts Group, the name of the committee that created the JPEG standard and other still picture coding standards.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The "Joint" stood for ISO TC97 WG8 and CCITT SGVIII.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Founded in 1986, the group developed the JPEG standard during the late 1980s.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The group published the JPEG standard in 1992.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In 1987, ISO TC 97 became ISO/IEC JTC 1 and, in 1992, CCITT became ITU-T.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Currently on the JTC1 side, JPEG is one of two sub-groups of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1, Subcommittee 29, Working Group 1 (ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 29/WG 1) – titled as *Coding of still pictures*.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] On the ITU-T side, ITU-T SG16 is the respective body.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The original JPEG Group was organized in 1986, issuing the first JPEG standard in 1992, which was approved in September 1992 as **ITU-T Recommendation T.81** and, in 1994, as **ISO/IEC 10918-1**.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The JPEG standard specifies the codec, which defines how an image is compressed into a stream of bytes and decompressed back into an image, but not the file format used to contain that stream.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The Exif and JFIF standards define the commonly used file formats for interchange of JPEG-compressed images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] JPEG standards are formally named as *Information technology – Digital compression and coding of continuous-tone still images*.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Ecma International TR/98 specifies the JPEG File Interchange Format (JFIF); the first edition was published in June 2009.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In 2002, Forgent Networks asserted that it owned and would enforce patent rights on the JPEG technology, arising from a patent that had been filed on 27 October 1986, and granted on 6 October 1987: U.S. patent 4,698,672 by Compression Labs' Wen-Hsiung Chen and Daniel J.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] While Forgent did not own Compression Labs at the time, Chen later sold Compression Labs to Forgent, before Chen went on to work for Cisco.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] This led to Forgent acquiring ownership over the patent.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Forgent's 2002 announcement created a furor reminiscent of Unisys' attempts to assert its rights over the GIF image compression standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The JPEG committee investigated the patent claims in 2002 and were of the opinion that they were invalidated by prior art, a view shared by various experts.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Between 2002 and 2004, Forgent was able to obtain about US$105 million by licensing their patent to some 30 companies.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In April 2004, Forgent sued 31 other companies to enforce further license payments.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In July of the same year, a consortium of 21 large computer companies filed a countersuit, with the goal of invalidating the patent.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In addition, Microsoft launched a separate lawsuit against Forgent in April 2005.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In February 2006, the United States Patent and Trademark Office agreed to re-examine Forgent's JPEG patent at the request of the Public Patent Foundation.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] On 26 May 2006, the USPTO found the patent invalid based on prior art.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The USPTO also found that Forgent knew about the prior art, yet it intentionally avoided telling the Patent Office.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] This made any appeal to reinstate the patent highly unlikely to succeed.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Forgent also possesses a similar patent granted by the European Patent Office in 1994, though it is unclear how enforceable it is.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] As of 27 October 2006, the U.S. patent's 20-year term appears to have expired, and in November 2006, Forgent agreed to abandon enforcement of patent claims against use of the JPEG standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The JPEG committee has as one of its explicit goals that their standards (in particular their baseline methods) be implementable without payment of license fees, and they have secured appropriate license rights for their JPEG 2000 standard from over 20 large organizations.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Beginning in August 2007, another company, Global Patent Holdings, LLC claimed that its patent (U.S. patent 5,253,341) issued in 1993, is infringed by the downloading of JPEG images on either a website or through e-mail.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] If not invalidated, this patent could apply to any website that displays JPEG images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The patent was under reexamination by the U.S.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Patent and Trademark Office from 2000 to 2007; in July 2007, the Patent Office revoked all of the original claims of the patent but found that an additional claim proposed by Global Patent Holdings (claim 17) was valid.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Global Patent Holdings then filed a number of lawsuits based on claim 17 of its patent.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In its first two lawsuits following the reexamination, both filed in Chicago, Illinois, Global Patent Holdings sued the Green Bay Packers, CDW, Motorola, Apple, Orbitz, OfficeMax, Caterpillar, Kraft and Peapod as defendants.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] A third lawsuit was filed on 5 December 2007, in South Florida against ADT Security Services, AutoNation, Florida Crystals Corp., HearUSA, MovieTickets.com, Ocwen Financial Corp. and Tire Kingdom, and a fourth lawsuit on 8 January 2008, in South Florida against the Boca Raton Resort & Club.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] A fifth lawsuit was filed against Global Patent Holdings in Nevada.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] That lawsuit was filed by Zappos.com, Inc., which was allegedly threatened by Global Patent Holdings, and sought a judicial declaration that the '341 patent is invalid and not infringed.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Patent and Trademark Office to reexamine the sole remaining claim of the '341 patent on the basis of new prior art.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Patent and Trademark Office agreed to reexamine the '341 patent, finding that the new prior art raised substantial new questions regarding the patent's validity.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In light of the reexamination, the accused infringers in four of the five pending lawsuits have filed motions to suspend (stay) their cases until completion of the U.S.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Patent and Trademark Office's review of the '341 patent.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] On 23 April 2008, a judge presiding over the two lawsuits in Chicago, Illinois granted the motions in those cases.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] On 22 July 2008, the Patent Office issued the first "Office Action" of the second reexamination, finding the claim invalid based on nineteen separate grounds.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] On 24 November 2009, a Reexamination Certificate was issued cancelling all claims.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Beginning in 2011 and continuing as of early 2013, an entity known as Princeton Digital Image Corporation, based in Eastern Texas, began suing large numbers of companies for alleged infringement of U.S. patent 4,813,056.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Princeton claims that the JPEG image compression standard infringes the '056 patent and has sued large numbers of websites, retailers, camera and device manufacturers and resellers.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The patent was originally owned and assigned to General Electric.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The patent expired in December 2007, but Princeton has sued large numbers of companies for "past infringement" of this patent.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] General Electric's involvement in the suit is unknown, although court records indicate that it assigned the patent to Princeton in 2009 and retains certain rights in the patent.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The JPEG compression algorithm operates at its best on photographs and paintings of realistic scenes with smooth variations of tone and color.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] For web usage, where reducing the amount of data used for an image is important for responsive presentation, JPEG's compression benefits make JPEG popular.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] JPEG/Exif is also the most common format saved by digital cameras.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] However, JPEG is not well suited for line drawings and other textual or iconic graphics, where the sharp contrasts between adjacent pixels can cause noticeable artifacts.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Such images are better saved in a lossless graphics format such as TIFF, GIF, PNG, or a raw image format.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The JPEG standard includes a lossless coding mode, but that mode is not supported in most products.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] As the typical use of JPEG is a lossy compression method, which reduces the image fidelity, it is inappropriate for exact reproduction of imaging data (such as some scientific and medical imaging applications and certain technical image processing work).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] JPEG is also not well suited to files that will undergo multiple edits, as some image quality is lost each time the image is recompressed, particularly if the image is cropped or shifted, or if encoding parameters are changed – see digital generation loss for details.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] To prevent image information loss during sequential and repetitive editing, the first edit can be saved in a lossless format, subsequently edited in that format, then finally published as JPEG for distribution.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] JPEG uses a lossy form of compression based on the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] This mathematical operation converts each frame/field of the video source from the spatial (2D) domain into the frequency domain (a.k.a. transform domain).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] A perceptual model based loosely on how the human psychovisual system discards high-frequency information, i.e. sharp transitions in intensity, and color hue.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In the transform domain, the process of reducing information is called quantization.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The quantized coefficients are then sequenced and losslessly packed into the output bitstream.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Nearly all software implementations of JPEG permit user control over the compression ratio (as well as other optional parameters), allowing the user to trade off picture-quality for smaller file size.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In embedded applications (such as miniDV, which uses a similar DCT-compression scheme), the parameters are pre-selected and fixed for the application.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The compression method is usually lossy, meaning that some original image information is lost and cannot be restored, possibly affecting image quality.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] There is an optional lossless mode defined in the JPEG standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] However, this mode is not widely supported in products.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] There is also an interlaced *progressive* JPEG format, in which data is compressed in multiple passes of progressively higher detail.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] This is ideal for large images that will be displayed while downloading over a slow connection, allowing a reasonable preview after receiving only a portion of the data.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] However, support for progressive JPEGs is not universal.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] When progressive JPEGs are received by programs that do not support them (such as versions of Internet Explorer before Windows 7) the software displays the image only after it has been completely downloaded.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] There are also many medical imaging, traffic and camera applications that create and process 12-bit JPEG images both grayscale and color.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] 12-bit JPEG format is included in an Extended part of the JPEG specification.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The libjpeg codec supports 12-bit JPEG and there even exists a high-performance version.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Several alterations to a JPEG image can be performed losslessly (that is, without recompression and the associated quality loss) as long as the image size is a multiple of 1 MCU block (Minimum Coded Unit) (usually 16 pixels in both directions, for 4:2:0 chroma subsampling).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Blocks can be rotated in 90-degree increments, flipped in the horizontal, vertical and diagonal axes and moved about in the image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Not all blocks from the original image need to be used in the modified one.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The top and left edge of a JPEG image must lie on an 8 × 8 pixel block boundary (or 16 × 16 pixel for larger MCU sizes), but the bottom and right edge need not do so.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] This limits the possible **lossless crop** operations, and prevents flips and rotations of an image whose bottom or right edge does not lie on a block boundary for all channels (because the edge would end up on top or left, where – as aforementioned – a block boundary is obligatory).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Rotations where the image is not a multiple of 8 or 16, which value depends upon the chroma subsampling, are not lossless.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Rotating such an image causes the blocks to be recomputed which results in loss of quality.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] When using lossless cropping, if the bottom or right side of the crop region is not on a block boundary, then the rest of the data from the partially used blocks will still be present in the cropped file and can be recovered.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] It is also possible to transform between baseline and progressive formats without any loss of quality, since the only difference is the order in which the coefficients are placed in the file.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Furthermore, several JPEG images can be losslessly joined, as long as they were saved with the same quality and the edges coincide with block boundaries.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The file format known as "JPEG Interchange Format" (JIF) is specified in Annex B of the standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Several additional standards have evolved to address these issues.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The first of these, released in 1992, was the JPEG File Interchange Format (JFIF), followed in recent years by Exchangeable image file format (Exif) and ICC color profiles.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Both of these formats use the actual JIF byte layout, consisting of different *markers*, but in addition, employ one of the JIF standard's extension points, namely the *application markers*: JFIF uses APP0, while Exif uses APP1.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Within these segments of the file that were left for future use in the JIF standard and are not read by it, these standards add specific metadata.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Thus, in some ways, JFIF is a cut-down version of the JIF standard in that it specifies certain constraints (such as not allowing all the different encoding modes), while in other ways, it is an extension of JIF due to the added metadata.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Image files that employ JPEG compression are commonly called "JPEG files", and are stored in variants of the JIF image format.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Most image capture devices (such as digital cameras) that output JPEG are actually creating files in the Exif format, the format that the camera industry has standardized on for metadata interchange.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] On the other hand, since the Exif standard does not allow color profiles, most image editing software stores JPEG in JFIF format, and includes the APP1 segment from the Exif file to include the metadata in an almost-compliant way; the JFIF standard is interpreted somewhat flexibly.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Strictly speaking, the JFIF and Exif standards are incompatible, because each specifies that its marker segment (APP0 or APP1, respectively) appear first.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] In practice, most JPEG files contain a JFIF marker segment that precedes the Exif header.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] This allows older readers to correctly handle the older format JFIF segment, while newer readers also decode the following Exif segment, being less strict about requiring it to appear first.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] The most common filename extensions for files employing JPEG compression are **`.jpg`** and **`.jpeg`**, though `.jpe`, `.jfif` and `.jif` are also used.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] It is also possible for JPEG data to be embedded in other file types – TIFF encoded files often embed a JPEG image as a thumbnail of the main image; and MP3 files can contain a JPEG of cover art in the ID3v2 tag.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Many JPEG files embed an ICC color profile (color space).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Commonly used color profiles include sRGB and Adobe RGB.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Because these color spaces use a non-linear transformation, the dynamic range of an 8-bit JPEG file is about 11 stops; see gamma curve.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] If the image doesn't specify color profile information (*untagged*), the color space is assumed to be sRGB for the purposes of display on webpages.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] A JPEG image consists of a sequence of *segments*, each beginning with a *marker*, each of which begins with a 0xFF byte, followed by a byte indicating what kind of marker it is.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Some markers consist of just those two bytes; others are followed by two bytes (high then low), indicating the length of marker-specific payload data that follows.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] (The length includes the two bytes for the length, but not the two bytes for the marker.) Some markers are followed by entropy-coded data; the length of such a marker does not include the entropy-coded data.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Within the entropy-coded data, after any 0xFF byte, a 0x00 byte is inserted by the encoder before the next byte, so that there does not appear to be a marker where none is intended, preventing framing errors.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] This technique, called byte stuffing (see JPEG specification section F.1.2.3), is only applied to the entropy-coded data, not to marker payload data.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] There are other *Start Of Frame* markers that introduce other kinds of JPEG encodings.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Since several vendors might use the same APP*n* marker type, application-specific markers often begin with a standard or vendor name (e.g., "Exif" or "Adobe") or some other identifying string.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] At a restart marker, block-to-block predictor variables are reset, and the bitstream is synchronized to a byte boundary.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Restart markers provide means for recovery after bitstream error, such as transmission over an unreliable network or file corruption.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p01] Since the runs of macroblocks between restart markers may be independently decoded, these runs may be decoded in parallel.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Although a JPEG file can be encoded in various ways, most commonly it is done with JFIF encoding.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The resolution of the chroma data is reduced, usually by a factor of 2 or 3.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This reflects the fact that the eye is less sensitive to fine color details than to fine brightness details.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The image is split into blocks of 8×8 pixels, and for each block, each of the Y, CB, and CR data undergoes the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] A DCT is similar to a Fourier transform in the sense that it produces a kind of spatial frequency spectrum.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The amplitudes of the frequency components are quantized.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Human vision is much more sensitive to small variations in color or brightness over large areas than to the strength of high-frequency brightness variations.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Therefore, the magnitudes of the high-frequency components are stored with a lower accuracy than the low-frequency components.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The quality setting of the encoder (for example 50 or 95 on a scale of 0–100 in the Independent JPEG Group's library) affects to what extent the resolution of each frequency component is reduced.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] If an excessively low quality setting is used, the high-frequency components are discarded altogether.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The resulting data for all 8×8 blocks is further compressed with a lossless algorithm, a variant of Huffman encoding.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The decoding process reverses these steps, except the *quantization* because it is irreversible.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In the remainder of this section, the encoding and decoding processes are described in more detail.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Many of the options in the JPEG standard are not commonly used, and as mentioned above, most image software uses the simpler JFIF format when creating a JPEG file, which among other things specifies the encoding method.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Here is a brief description of one of the more common methods of encoding when applied to an input that has 24 bits per pixel (eight each of red, green, and blue).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This particular option is a lossy data compression method.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] First, the image should be converted from RGB (by default sRGB, but other color spaces are possible) into a different color space called Y′CBCR (or, informally, YCbCr).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It has three components Y', CB and CR: the Y' component represents the brightness of a pixel, and the CB and CR components represent the chrominance (split into blue and red components).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This is basically the same color space as used by digital color television as well as digital video including video DVDs.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The Y′CBCR color space conversion allows greater compression without a significant effect on perceptual image quality (or greater perceptual image quality for the same compression).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The compression is more efficient because the brightness information, which is more important to the eventual perceptual quality of the image, is confined to a single channel.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This more closely corresponds to the perception of color in the human visual system.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The color transformation also improves compression by statistical decorrelation.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] A particular conversion to Y′CBCR is specified in the JFIF standard, and should be performed for the resulting JPEG file to have maximum compatibility.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] However, some JPEG implementations in "highest quality" mode do not apply this step and instead keep the color information in the RGB color model, where the image is stored in separate channels for red, green and blue brightness components.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This results in less efficient compression, and would not likely be used when file size is especially important.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Due to the densities of color- and brightness-sensitive receptors in the human eye, humans can see considerably more fine detail in the brightness of an image (the Y' component) than in the hue and color saturation of an image (the Cb and Cr components).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Using this knowledge, encoders can be designed to compress images more efficiently.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The transformation into the Y′CBCR color model enables the next usual step, which is to reduce the spatial resolution of the Cb and Cr components (called "downsampling" or "chroma subsampling").
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The ratios at which the downsampling is ordinarily done for JPEG images are 4:4:4 (no downsampling), 4:2:2 (reduction by a factor of 2 in the horizontal direction), or (most commonly) 4:2:0 (reduction by a factor of 2 in both the horizontal and vertical directions).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] For the rest of the compression process, Y', Cb and Cr are processed separately and in a very similar manner.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] After subsampling, each channel must be split into 8×8 blocks.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Depending on chroma subsampling, this yields Minimum Coded Unit (MCU) blocks of size 8×8 (4:4:4 – no subsampling), 16×8 (4:2:2), or most commonly 16×16 (4:2:0).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In video compression MCUs are called macroblocks.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] If the data for a channel does not represent an integer number of blocks then the encoder must fill the remaining area of the incomplete blocks with some form of dummy data.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Next, each 8×8 block of each component (Y, Cb, Cr) is converted to a frequency-domain representation, using a normalized, two-dimensional type-II discrete cosine transform (DCT), see Citation 1 in discrete cosine transform.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The DCT is sometimes referred to as "type-II DCT" in the context of a family of transforms as in discrete cosine transform, and the corresponding inverse (IDCT) is denoted as "type-III DCT".
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Before computing the DCT of the 8×8 block, its values are shifted from a positive range to one centered on zero.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] For an 8-bit image, each entry in the original block falls in the range $[0,255]$ .
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The midpoint of the range (in this case, the value 128) is subtracted from each entry to produce a data range that is centered on zero, so that the modified range is $[-128,127]$ .
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This step reduces the dynamic range requirements in the DCT processing stage that follows.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Note the top-left corner entry with the rather large magnitude.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This is the DC coefficient (also called the constant component), which defines the basic hue for the entire block.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The remaining 63 coefficients are the AC coefficients (also called the alternating components).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The advantage of the DCT is its tendency to aggregate most of the signal in one corner of the result, as may be seen above.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The quantization step to follow accentuates this effect while simultaneously reducing the overall size of the DCT coefficients, resulting in a signal that is easy to compress efficiently in the entropy stage.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The DCT temporarily increases the bit-depth of the data, since the DCT coefficients of an 8-bit/component image take up to 11 or more bits (depending on fidelity of the DCT calculation) to store.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This may force the codec to temporarily use 16-bit numbers to hold these coefficients, doubling the size of the image representation at this point; these values are typically reduced back to 8-bit values by the quantization step.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The temporary increase in size at this stage is not a performance concern for most JPEG implementations, since typically only a very small part of the image is stored in full DCT form at any given time during the image encoding or decoding process.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The human eye is good at seeing small differences in brightness over a relatively large area, but not so good at distinguishing the exact strength of a high frequency brightness variation.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This allows one to greatly reduce the amount of information in the high frequency components.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This is done by simply dividing each component in the frequency domain by a constant for that component, and then rounding to the nearest integer.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This rounding operation is the only lossy operation in the whole process (other than chroma subsampling) if the DCT computation is performed with sufficiently high precision.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] As a result of this, it is typically the case that many of the higher frequency components are rounded to zero, and many of the rest become small positive or negative numbers, which take many fewer bits to represent.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The elements in the quantization matrix control the compression ratio, with larger values producing greater compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] where G is the unquantized DCT coefficients; Q is the quantization matrix above; and B is the quantized DCT coefficients.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Notice that most of the higher-frequency elements of the sub-block (i.e., those with an *x* or *y* spatial frequency greater than 4) are quantized into zero values.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Entropy coding is a special form of lossless data compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It involves arranging the image components in a "zigzag" order employing run-length encoding (RLE) algorithm that groups similar frequencies together, inserting length coding zeros, and then using Huffman coding on what is left.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The JPEG standard also allows, but does not require, decoders to support the use of arithmetic coding, which is mathematically superior to Huffman coding.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] However, this feature has rarely been used, as it was historically covered by patents requiring royalty-bearing licenses, and because it is slower to encode and decode compared to Huffman coding.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Arithmetic coding typically makes files about 5–7% smaller.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The previous quantized DC coefficient is used to predict the current quantized DC coefficient.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The difference between the two is encoded rather than the actual value.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The encoding of the 63 quantized AC coefficients does not use such prediction differencing.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The zigzag sequence for the above quantized coefficients are shown below.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] If the *i*-th block is represented by $B_{i}$ and positions within each block are represented by $(p,q)$ where $p=0,1,...,7$ and $q=0,1,...,7$ , then any coefficient in the DCT image can be represented as $B_{i}(p,q)$ .
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This encoding mode is called baseline *sequential* encoding.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Baseline JPEG also supports *progressive* encoding.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] While sequential encoding encodes coefficients of a single block at a time (in a zigzag manner), progressive encoding encodes similar-positioned batch of coefficients of all blocks in one go (called a *scan*), followed by the next batch of coefficients of all blocks, and so on.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Once all similar-positioned coefficients have been encoded, the next position to be encoded is the one occurring next in the zigzag traversal as indicated in the figure above.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In the rest of the article, it is assumed that the coefficient pattern generated is due to sequential mode.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In order to encode the above generated coefficient pattern, JPEG uses Huffman encoding.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The JPEG standard provides general-purpose Huffman tables; encoders may also choose to generate Huffman tables optimized for the actual frequency distributions in images being encoded.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The run-length encoding works by examining each non-zero AC coefficient x and determining how many zeroes came before the previous AC coefficient.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Both *RUNLENGTH* and *SIZE* rest on the same byte, meaning that each only contains four bits of information.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The higher bits deal with the number of zeroes, while the lower bits denote the number of bits necessary to encode the value of x.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This has the immediate implication of *Symbol 1* being only able store information regarding the first 15 zeroes preceding the non-zero AC coefficient.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] However, JPEG defines two special Huffman code words.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] One is for ending the sequence prematurely when the remaining coefficients are zero (called "End-of-Block" or "EOB"), and another when the run of zeroes goes beyond 15 before reaching a non-zero AC coefficient.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In such a case where 16 zeroes are encountered before a given non-zero AC coefficient, *Symbol 1* is encoded "specially" as: (15, 0)(0).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The overall process continues until "EOB" – denoted by (0, 0) – is reached.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] (The first value in the matrix, −26, is the DC coefficient; it is not encoded the same way.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] From here, frequency calculations are made based on occurrences of the coefficients.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In our example block, most of the quantized coefficients are small numbers that are not preceded immediately by a zero coefficient.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] These more-frequent cases will be represented by shorter code words.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The resulting compression ratio can be varied according to need by being more or less aggressive in the divisors used in the quantization phase.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Ten to one compression usually results in an image that cannot be distinguished by eye from the original.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] A compression ratio of 100:1 is usually possible, but will look distinctly artifacted compared to the original.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The appropriate level of compression depends on the use to which the image will be put.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Those who use the World Wide Web may be familiar with the irregularities known as compression artifacts that appear in JPEG images, which may take the form of noise around contrasting edges (especially curves and corners), or "blocky" images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] These are due to the quantization step of the JPEG algorithm.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] They are especially noticeable around sharp corners between contrasting colors (text is a good example, as it contains many such corners).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The analogous artifacts in MPEG video are referred to as *mosquito noise,* as the resulting "edge busyness" and spurious dots, which change over time, resemble mosquitoes swarming around the object.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] These artifacts can be reduced by choosing a lower level of compression; they may be completely avoided by saving an image using a lossless file format, though this will result in a larger file size.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The images created with ray-tracing programs have noticeable blocky shapes on the terrain.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Certain low-intensity compression artifacts might be acceptable when simply viewing the images, but can be emphasized if the image is subsequently processed, usually resulting in unacceptable quality.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Consider the example below, demonstrating the effect of lossy compression on an edge detection processing step.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Some programs allow the user to vary the amount by which individual blocks are compressed.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Stronger compression is applied to areas of the image that show fewer artifacts.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This way it is possible to manually reduce JPEG file size with less loss of quality.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Since the quantization stage *always* results in a loss of information, JPEG standard is always a lossy compression codec.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] (Information is lost both in quantizing and rounding of the floating-point numbers.) Even if the quantization matrix is a matrix of ones, information will still be lost in the rounding step.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Decoding to display the image consists of doing all the above in reverse.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] which closely resembles the original DCT coefficient matrix for the top-left portion.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Slight differences are noticeable between the original (top) and decompressed image (bottom), which is most readily seen in the bottom-left corner.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In general, the decompression process may produce values outside the original input range of $[0,255]$ .
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] If this occurs, the decoder needs to clip the output values so as to keep them within that range to prevent overflow when storing the decompressed image with the original bit depth.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The error is most noticeable in the bottom-left corner where the bottom-left pixel becomes darker than the pixel to its immediate right.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The required implementation precision of a JPEG codec is implicitly defined through the requirements formulated for compliance to the JPEG standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] These requirements are specified in ITU.T Recommendation T.83 | ISO/IEC 10918-2.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] For example, the output of a decoder implementation must not exceed an error of one quantization unit in the DCT domain when applied to the reference testing codestreams provided as part of the above standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] While unusual, and unlike many other and more modern standards, ITU.T T.83 | ISO/IEC 10918-2 does not formulate error bounds in the image domain.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] JPEG compression artifacts blend well into photographs with detailed non-uniform textures, allowing higher compression ratios.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Notice how a higher compression ratio first affects the high-frequency textures in the upper-left corner of the image, and how the contrasting lines become more fuzzy.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The very high compression ratio severely affects the quality of the image, although the overall colors and image form are still recognizable.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] However, the precision of colors suffer less (for a human eye) than the precision of contours (based on luminance).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] For information, the uncompressed 24-bit RGB bitmap image below (73,242 pixels) would require 219,726 bytes (excluding all other information headers).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The filesizes indicated below include the internal JPEG information headers and some metadata.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] For highest quality images (Q=100), about 8.25 bits per color pixel is required.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] On grayscale images, a minimum of 6.5 bits per pixel is enough (a comparable Q=100 quality color information requires about 25% more encoded bits).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The highest quality image below (Q=100) is encoded at nine bits per color pixel, the medium quality image (Q=25) uses one bit per color pixel.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] For most applications, the quality factor should not go below 0.75 bit per pixel (Q=12.5), as demonstrated by the low quality image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The image at lowest quality uses only 0.13 bit per pixel, and displays very poor color.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This is useful when the image will be displayed in a significantly scaled-down size.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] A method for creating better quantization matrices for a given image quality using PSNR instead of the Q factor is described in Minguillón & Pujol (2001).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The medium quality photo uses only 4.3% of the storage space required for the uncompressed image, but has little noticeable loss of detail or visible artifacts.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] However, once a certain threshold of compression is passed, compressed images show increasingly visible defects.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] See the article on rate–distortion theory for a mathematical explanation of this threshold effect.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] A particular limitation of JPEG in this regard is its non-overlapped 8×8 block transform structure.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] More modern designs such as JPEG 2000 and JPEG XR exhibit a more graceful degradation of quality as the bit usage decreases – by using transforms with a larger spatial extent for the lower frequency coefficients and by using overlapping transform basis functions.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] From 2004 to 2008, new research emerged on ways to further compress the data contained in JPEG images without modifying the represented image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This has applications in scenarios where the original image is only available in JPEG format, and its size needs to be reduced for archiving or transmission.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Standard general-purpose compression tools cannot significantly compress JPEG files.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Typically, such methods can compress existing JPEG files between 15 and 25 percent, and for JPEGs compressed at low-quality settings, can produce improvements of up to 65%.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Several programs are available for lossless recompression of JPEG files.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The files produced by such programs are not compatible with the JPEG standard and require special software to decode.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] JPS is a stereoscopic JPEG image used for creating 3D effects from 2D images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It contains two static images, one for the left eye and one for the right eye; encoded as two side-by-side images in a single JPEG file.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] JPEG Stereoscopic (JPS, extension .jps) is a JPEG-based format for stereoscopic images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It has a range of configurations stored in the JPEG APP3 marker field, but usually contains one image of double width, representing two images of identical size in cross-eyed (i.e. left frame on the right half of the image and vice versa) side-by-side arrangement.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This file format can be viewed as a JPEG without any special software, or can be processed for rendering in other modes.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] JPEG Multi-Picture Format (MPO, extension .mpo) is a JPEG-based format for storing multiple images in a single file.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It contains two or more JPEG files concatenated together.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It also defines a JPEG APP2 marker segment for image description.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Various devices use it to store 3D images, such as Fujifilm FinePix Real 3D W1, HTC Evo 3D, JVC GY-HMZ1U AVCHD/MVC extension camcorder, Nintendo 3DS, Panasonic Lumix DMC-TZ20, DMC-TZ30, DMC-TZ60, DMC-TS4 (FT4), and Sony DSC-HX7V.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Other devices use it to store "preview images" that can be displayed on a TV.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In the last few years, due to the growing use of stereoscopic images, much effort has been spent by the scientific community to develop algorithms for stereoscopic image compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] A very important implementation of a JPEG codec is the free programming library **libjpeg** of the Independent JPEG Group.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It was first published in 1991 and was key for the success of the standard.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] This library was used in countless applications.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The development went quiet in 1998; when libjpeg resurfaced with the 2009 version 7, it broke ABI compatibility with previous versions.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Version 8 of 2010 introduced non-standard extensions, a decision criticized by the original IJG leader Tom Lane.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] ISO/IEC Joint Photographic Experts Group maintains the other reference software implementation under the JPEG XT heading.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It can encode both base JPEG (ISO/IEC 10918-1 and 18477–1) and JPEG XT extensions (ISO/IEC 18477 Parts 2 and 6–9), as well as JPEG-LS (ISO/IEC 14495).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In 2016, "JPEG on steroids" was introduced as an option for the ISO JPEG XT reference implementation.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] There is persistent interest in encoding JPEG in unconventional ways that maximize image quality for a given file size.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In 2014, Mozilla created **MozJPEG** from libjpeg-turbo, a slower but higher-quality encoder intended for web images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In March 2017, Google released the open source project Guetzli, which trades off a much longer encoding time for smaller file size (similar to what Zopfli does for PNG and other lossless data formats).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] In April 2024, Google introduced **Jpegli**, a new JPEG coding library that offers enhanced capabilities and a 35% compression ratio improvement at high quality compression settings, while the coding speed is comparable with MozJPEG.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The Joint Photographic Experts Group has developed several newer standards meant to complement or replace the functionality of the original JPEG format.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Originating in 1993 and published as ISO-14495-1/ITU-T.87, JPEG LS offers a low-complexity lossless file format which was more efficient than JPEG's original lossless implementation.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It also features a lossy mode close to lossless.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Its functionality is largely limited to that, and largely shares the same limitations of the original JPEG in other aspects.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] JPEG 2000 was published as ISO/IEC 15444 in December 2000.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It is based on a discrete wavelet transform (DWT) and was designed to completely replace the original JPEG standard and exceed it in every way.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It allows up to 38 bits per colour channel and 16384 channels, more than any other format, with a multitude of colour spaces, and thus high dynamic range (HDR).
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Furthermore, it supports alpha transparency coding, billions-by-billions pixel images, which is also more than any other format, and lossless compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It has significantly improved lossy compression ratio with significantly less visible artefacts at strong compression levels.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] JPEG XT (ISO/IEC 18477) was published in June 2015; it extends base JPEG format with support for higher integer bit depths (up to 16 bit), high dynamic range imaging and floating-point coding, lossless coding, and alpha channel coding.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Extensions are backward compatible with the base JPEG/JFIF file format and 8-bit lossy compressed image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] JPEG XT uses an extensible file format based on JFIF.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Extension layers are used to modify the JPEG 8-bit base layer and restore the high-resolution image.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] Existing software is forward compatible and can read the JPEG XT binary stream, though it would only decode the base 8-bit layer.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] It replaces the JPEG format with a new DCT-based royalty-free format and allows efficient transcoding as a storage option for traditional JPEG images.
[src:jpeg-compression/jpeg-p02] The new format is designed to exceed the still image compression performance shown by HEIF HM, Daala and WebP.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] In information technology, **lossy compression**, or **irreversible compression**, is the class of data compression methods that uses inexact approximations and partial data discarding to represent the content.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] These techniques are used to reduce data size for storing, handling, and transmitting content.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Higher degrees of approximation create coarser images as more details are removed.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] This is opposed to lossless data compression (reversible data compression) which does not degrade the data.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The amount of data reduction possible using lossy compression is much higher than using lossless techniques.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Well-designed lossy compression technology often reduces file sizes significantly before degradation is noticed by the end-user.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Even when noticeable by the user, further data reduction may be desirable (e.g., for real-time communication or to reduce transmission times or storage needs).
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The most widely used lossy compression algorithm is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Lossy compression is most commonly used to compress multimedia data (audio, video, and images), especially in applications such as streaming media and internet telephony.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] By contrast, lossless compression is typically required for text and data files, such as bank records and text articles.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] It can be advantageous to make a master lossless file which can then be used to produce additional copies from.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] This allows one to avoid basing new compressed copies on a lossy source file, which would yield additional artifacts and further unnecessary information loss.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] It is possible to compress many types of digital data in a way that reduces the size of a computer file needed to store it, or the bandwidth needed to transmit it, with no loss of the full information contained in the original file.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] A picture, for example, is converted to a digital file by considering it to be an array of dots and specifying the color and brightness of each dot.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The original data contains a certain amount of information, and there is a lower bound to the size of a file that can still carry all the information.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Basic information theory says that there is an absolute limit in reducing the size of this data.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] When data is compressed, its entropy increases, and it cannot increase indefinitely.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] For example, a compressed ZIP file is smaller than its original, but repeatedly compressing the same file will not reduce the size to nothing.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Most compression algorithms can recognize when further compression would be pointless and would in fact increase the size of the data.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] In many cases, files or data streams contain more information than is needed.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] For example, a picture may have more detail than the eye can distinguish when reproduced at the largest size intended; likewise, an audio file does not need a lot of fine detail during a very loud passage.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Developing lossy compression techniques as closely matched to human perception as possible is a complex task.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Sometimes the ideal is a file that provides exactly the same perception as the original, with as much digital information as possible removed; other times, perceptible loss of quality is considered a valid tradeoff.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The terms "irreversible" and "reversible" are preferred over "lossy" and "lossless" respectively for some applications, such as medical image compression, to circumvent the negative implications of "loss".
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The type and amount of loss can affect the utility of the images.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Artifacts or undesirable effects of compression may be clearly discernible yet the result still useful for the intended purpose.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Or lossy compressed images may be 'visually lossless', or in the case of medical images, so-called diagnostically acceptable irreversible compression (DAIC) may have been applied.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Some forms of lossy compression can be thought of as an application of transform coding, which is a type of data compression used for digital images, digital audio signals, and digital video.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The transformation is typically used to enable better (more targeted) quantization.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Knowledge of the application is used to choose information to discard, thereby lowering its bandwidth.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The remaining information can then be compressed via a variety of methods.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] When the output is decoded, the result may not be identical to the original input, but is expected to be close enough for the purpose of the application.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The most common form of lossy compression is a transform coding method, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which was first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] DCT is the most widely used form of lossy compression, for popular image compression formats (such as JPEG), video coding standards (such as MPEG and H.264/AVC) and audio compression formats (such as MP3 and AAC).
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] In the case of audio data, a popular form of transform coding is perceptual coding, which transforms the raw data to a domain that more accurately reflects the information content.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] For example, rather than expressing a sound file as the amplitude levels over time, one may express it as the frequency spectrum over time, which corresponds more accurately to human audio perception.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] This is because uncompressed audio can only reduce file size by lowering bit rate or depth, whereas compressing audio can reduce size while maintaining bit rate and depth.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] This compression becomes a selective loss of the least significant data, rather than losing data across the board.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Further, a transform coding may provide a better domain for manipulating or otherwise editing the data – for example, equalization of audio is most naturally expressed in the frequency domain (boost the bass, for instance) rather than in the raw time domain.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] From this point of view, perceptual encoding is not essentially about *discarding* data, but rather about a *better representation* of data.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Another use is for backward compatibility and graceful degradation: in color television, encoding color via a luminance-chrominance transform domain (such as YUV) means that black-and-white sets display the luminance, while ignoring the color information.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Lossy compression formats suffer from generation loss: repeatedly compressing and decompressing the file will cause it to progressively lose quality.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] This is in contrast with lossless data compression, where data will not be lost via the use of such a procedure.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Information-theoretical foundations for lossy data compression are provided by rate-distortion theory.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Much like the use of probability in optimal coding theory, rate-distortion theory heavily draws on Bayesian estimation and decision theory in order to model perceptual distortion and even aesthetic judgment.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] In some systems the two techniques are combined, with transform codecs being used to compress the error signals generated by the predictive stage.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The advantage of lossy methods over lossless methods is that in some cases a lossy method can produce a much smaller compressed file than any lossless method, while still meeting the requirements of the application.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Lossy methods are most often used for compressing sound, images or videos.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] This is because these types of data are intended for human interpretation where the mind can easily "fill in the blanks" or see past very minor errors or inconsistencies – ideally lossy compression is transparent (imperceptible), which can be verified via an ABX test.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Data files using lossy compression are smaller in size and thus cost less to store and to transmit over the Internet, a crucial consideration for streaming video services such as Netflix and streaming audio services such as Spotify.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] When a user acquires a lossily compressed file, (for example, to reduce download time) the retrieved file can be quite different from the original at the bit level while being indistinguishable to the human ear or eye for most practical purposes.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Many compression methods focus on the idiosyncrasies of human physiology, taking into account, for instance, that the human eye can see only certain wavelengths of light.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The psychoacoustic model describes how sound can be highly compressed without degrading perceived quality.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Flaws caused by lossy compression that are noticeable to the human eye or ear are known as compression artifacts.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The compression ratio (that is, the size of the compressed file compared to that of the uncompressed file) of lossy video codecs is nearly always far superior to that of the audio and still-image equivalents.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] An important caveat about lossy compression (formally transcoding), is that editing lossily compressed files causes digital generation loss from the re-encoding.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] This can be avoided by only producing lossy files from (lossless) originals and only editing (copies of) original files, such as images in raw image format instead of JPEG.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] If data which has been compressed lossily is decoded and compressed losslessly, the size of the result can be comparable with the size of the data before lossy compression, but the data already lost cannot be recovered.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] When deciding to use lossy conversion without keeping the original, format conversion may be needed in the future to achieve compatibility with software or devices (format shifting), or to avoid paying patent royalties for decoding or distribution of compressed files.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] By modifying the compressed data directly without decoding and re-encoding, some editing of lossily compressed files without degradation of quality is possible.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Editing which reduces the file size as if it had been compressed to a greater degree, but without more loss than this, is sometimes also possible.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The primary programs for lossless editing of JPEGs are `jpegtran`, and the derived `exiftran` (which also preserves Exif information), and Jpegcrop (which provides a Windows interface).
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] These allow the image to be cropped, rotated, flipped, and flopped, or even converted to grayscale (by dropping the chrominance channel).
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] While unwanted information is destroyed, the quality of the remaining portion is unchanged.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Some other transforms are possible to some extent, such as joining images with the same encoding (composing side by side, as on a grid) or pasting images such as logos onto existing images (both via Jpegjoin), or scaling.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] The freeware Windows-only IrfanView has some lossless JPEG operations in its `JPG_TRANSFORM` plugin.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Metadata, such as ID3 tags, Vorbis comments, or Exif information, can usually be modified or removed without modifying the underlying data.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Some well-known designs that have this capability include JPEG 2000 for still images and H.264/MPEG-4 AVC based Scalable Video Coding for video.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Such schemes have also been standardized for older designs as well, such as JPEG images with progressive encoding, and MPEG-2 and MPEG-4 Part 2 video, although those prior schemes had limited success in terms of adoption into real-world common usage.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Similar techniques are used in mipmaps, pyramid representations, and more sophisticated scale space methods.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Some audio formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction which when combined reproduce the original signal; the correction can be stripped, leaving a smaller, lossily compressed, file.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, OptimFROG DualStream, and DTS-HD Master Audio in lossless (XLL) mode).
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Researchers have performed lossy compression on text by either using a thesaurus to substitute short words for long ones, or generative text techniques, although these sometimes fall into the related category of lossy data conversion.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] A general kind of lossy compression is to lower the resolution of an image, as in image scaling, particularly decimation.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] One may also remove less "lower information" parts of an image, such as by seam carving.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Many media transforms, such as Gaussian blur, are, like lossy compression, irreversible: the original signal cannot be reconstructed from the transformed signal.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] However, in general these will have the same size as the original, and are not a form of compression.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Lowering resolution has practical uses, as the NASA New Horizons craft transmitted thumbnails of its encounter with Pluto-Charon before it sent the higher resolution images.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Another solution for slow connections is the usage of Image interlacing which progressively defines the image.
[src:jpeg-compression/lossy-compression] Thus a partial transmission is enough to preview the final image, in a lower resolution version, without creating a scaled and a full version too.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] Color quantization reduces the number of colors used in an image; this is important for displaying images on devices that support a limited number of colors and for efficiently compressing certain kinds of images.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] Most bitmap editors and many operating systems have built-in support for color quantization.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] Popular modern color quantization algorithms include the nearest color algorithm (for fixed palettes), the median cut algorithm, and an algorithm based on octrees.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] It is common to combine color quantization with dithering to create an impression of a larger number of colors and eliminate banding artifacts.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] Grayscale quantization, also known as gray level quantization, is a process in digital image processing that involves reducing the number of unique intensity levels (shades of gray) in an image while preserving its essential visual information.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] This technique is commonly used for simplifying images, reducing storage requirements, and facilitating processing operations.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] In grayscale quantization, an image with *N* intensity levels is converted into an image with a reduced number of levels, typically *L* levels, where *L*<*N*.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] The process involves mapping each pixel's original intensity value to one of the new intensity levels.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] One of the simplest methods of grayscale quantization is uniform quantization, where the intensity range is divided into equal intervals, and each interval is represented by a single intensity value.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] Let's say we have an image with intensity levels ranging from 0 to 255 (8-bit grayscale).
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] Each interval would be represented by the midpoint intensity value, resulting in intensity levels of 31, 95, 159, and 223 respectively.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] Let's quantize an original intensity value of 147 to 3 intensity levels.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] So, the quantized intensity value of 147 to 3 levels is 191.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] The human eye is fairly good at seeing small differences in brightness over a relatively large area, but not so good at distinguishing the exact strength of a high frequency (rapidly varying) brightness variation.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] This fact allows one to reduce the amount of information required by ignoring the high frequency components.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] This is the main lossy operation in the whole process.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] As a result of this, it is typically the case that many of the higher frequency components are rounded to zero, and many of the rest become small positive or negative numbers.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] As human vision is also more sensitive to luminance than chrominance, further compression can be obtained by working in a non-RGB color space which separates the two (e.g., YCbCr), and quantizing the channels separately.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] A typical video codec works by breaking the picture into discrete blocks (8×8 pixels in the case of MPEG).
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] These blocks can then be subjected to discrete cosine transform (DCT) to calculate the frequency components, both horizontally and vertically.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] The resulting block (the same size as the original block) is then pre-multiplied by the quantization scale code and divided element-wise by the quantization matrix, and rounding each resultant element.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] The quantization matrix is designed to provide more resolution to more perceivable frequency components over less perceivable components (usually lower frequencies over high frequencies) in addition to transforming as many components to 0, which can be encoded with greatest efficiency.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] Many video encoders (such as DivX, Xvid, and 3ivx) and compression standards (such as MPEG-2 and H.264/AVC) allow custom matrices to be used.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] The extent of the reduction may be varied by changing the quantizer scale code, taking up much less bandwidth than a full quantizer matrix.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] Typically this process will result in matrices with values primarily in the upper left (low frequency) corner.
[src:jpeg-compression/quantization-image-processing] By using a zig-zag ordering to group the non-zero entries and run-length encoding, the quantized matrix can be much more efficiently stored than the non-quantized version.
